"Stramma L., Schmidtko S., Levin L.A., Johnson G.C.","Ocean oxygen minima expansions and their biological impacts",2010,"Deep-Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers","57","4",,"587","595",,,10.1016/j.dsr.2010.01.005,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77949570743&partnerID=40&md5=5442d3a64091bb6971bdc8e902315258","IFM-GEOMAR, Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany; National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory, 7600 Sand Point Way NE, Seattle, WA 98115, United States; Integrative Oceanography Division, Scripps Institution of Oceanography, 9500 Gilman Drive, La Jolla, CA 92093-0218, United States","Stramma, L., IFM-GEOMAR, Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany; Schmidtko, S., IFM-GEOMAR, Leibniz-Institut für Meereswissenschaften, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory, 7600 Sand Point Way NE, Seattle, WA 98115, United States; Levin, L.A., Integrative Oceanography Division, Scripps Institution of Oceanography, 9500 Gilman Drive, La Jolla, CA 92093-0218, United States; Johnson, G.C., National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory, 7600 Sand Point Way NE, Seattle, WA 98115, United States","Climate models with biogeochemical components predict declines in oceanic dissolved oxygen with global warming. In coastal regimes oxygen deficits represent acute ecosystem perturbations. Here, we estimate dissolved oxygen differences across the global tropical and subtropical oceans within the oxygen minimum zone (200-700-dbar depth) between 1960-1974 (an early period with reliable data) and 1990-2008 (a recent period capturing ocean response to planetary warming). In most regions of the tropical Pacific, Atlantic, and Indian Oceans the oxygen content in the 200-700-dbar layer has declined. Furthermore, at 200 dbar, the area with O2 &lt;70 μmol kg-1, where some large mobile macro-organisms are unable to abide, has increased by 4.5 million km2. The tropical low oxygen zones have expanded horizontally and vertically. Subsurface oxygen has decreased adjacent to most continental shelves. However, oxygen has increased in some regions in the subtropical gyres at the depths analyzed. According to literature discussed below, fishing pressure is strong in the open ocean, which may make it difficult to isolate the impact of declining oxygen on fisheries. At shallower depths we predict habitat compression will occur for hypoxia-intolerant taxa, with eventual loss of biodiversity. Should past trends in observed oxygen differences continue into the future, shifts in animal distributions and changes in ecosystem structure could accelerate. © 2010 Elsevier Ltd.","Deoxygenation; Ecosystem changes; Hypoxia; Oxygen minimum zones; Tropical Atlantic; Tropical ocean; Tropical Pacific","Deoxygenation; Deoxygenations; Oxygen minimum zone; Tropical atlantic; Tropical ocean; Biodiversity; Climate models; Dissolution; Dissolved oxygen sensors; Ecosystems; Fisheries; Global warming; Oceanography; Tropics; Dissolved oxygen; biodiversity; biogeochemistry; climate modeling; continental shelf; dissolved oxygen; ecosystem structure; fishing; gyre; hypoxia; open ocean; oxygen minimum layer; population distribution; Atlantic Ocean; Indian Ocean; Pacific Ocean; Pacific Ocean (Tropical); Animalia",,,,,,"Andersson, J.H., Woulds, C., Schwartz, M., Cowie, G.L., Levin, L.A., Soetaert, K., Middelburg, J.J., Short-term fate of phytodetritus in sediments across the Arabian Sea Oxygen Minimum Zone (2008) Biogeosciences, 5, pp. 43-53; Attrill, M.J., Wright, J., Edwards, M., Climate-related increases in jellyfish frequency suggest a more gelatinous future for the North Sea (2007) Limnol. Oceanogr., 52, pp. 480-485; Bograd, S.J., Castro, C.G., Di Lorenzo, E., Palacios, D.M., Bailey, H., Gilly, 